Table

Missing Migrants Data Set

Obtained by the International Organization for Migration

The International Organization for Migration is an international organization which works closely with national governments, international government organizations and non-governmental organizations. They closely look at the issues related to migration and even report their findings to those organizations in hopes to create or improve policy to help migrants as they travel from their home countries to their intended destinations. While studying migrations, the IOM has compiled a lot of data from various sources to show the hardships the migrants are facing.

The data set we looked at provided 5 years worth of data from all regions of the world. The data set provided dates, how many survived the tough journeys, how many people are expected to be missing and how many are expected to have lost their lives in search of better quality of life. The data set also included the regions that were studied, how the migrants lost their lives (if possible as only skeletal remains were found) and who reported the data. It was very interesting to see that the source quality was included in the data set; meaning they looked at how reputable the sources are.

About Us

We are students at an Data Analytics Bootcamp at George Washingon University. This project serves as our last project in the program. The program is 6 months and now we are showcasing all material that we have learned throughout the program. We are a diverse group of all women (with one man). So our last project is based on a global scale.

About IOM

The IOM, or the International Organization for Migration is an organization that is focused on researching migration trends, try to ensure the health and safety of all migrants worldwide and are even involved with governments from around the world promoting policies that support migrant health and wellbeing. Especially during this difficult time where migrants are fleeing warzones from the Middle East or South American seeking a better life in the United States, the IOM is there to support these migrants to the best of their ability

Created by Cristy Brust, Hemani Choksi, Stefanie Kenyon, Olan Johnson and Ning Xie
